<strong>Associate Planning Director:</strong><br />
Associate Planning Director is a stepping-stone between Senior Planner and Planning Director.&nbsp; It is intended to be a role where senior planners prove their readiness to move to the Planning Director Role described above.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Associate Planning Directors must have all the core skills of a good strategic planner and must be well versed in all the strategic disciplines and core skills.&nbsp; Associate Planning Directors are developing their management skills and honing their leadership role before they are given full Planning Director responsibilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />
&nbsp;<br />
An APD will be expected to take on all of the planning responsibilities and some of the management responsibilities of key strategic initiatives on particular accounts.&nbsp; They will report to a PD or GPD but will be expected to be able to operate autonomous for key client meetings, internal leadership meetings and most of the day-to-day business of the assignment.&nbsp;&nbsp; APD&rsquo;s should already have demonstrated a significant amount of client leadership, strategic leadership and team-work to take clients to new and interesting strategic territories.&nbsp; They have to have shown that they can successfully take their strategic work to full execution and have proven success at delivering strategically driven creative work.&nbsp;&nbsp; APD&rsquo;s should have a portfolio of well articulated case studies (and ideally industry awards) that demonstrate the impact their thinking has had on a client&rsquo;s business.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
APD must also demonstrate solid craft skills in all core areas of planning from research and insights, business strategy, media and connections thinking, analytics, cultural trends digital and social strategies.<br />
